  "prompt": "Does it cost Starbucks more for the cup their coffee goes in, or the actual coffee itself?",
  "response": "The cost of the cup that Starbucks uses for its coffee is generally higher than the cost of the coffee itself. This is due to various factors, including the materials used for the cups, their design, and the fact that they are often made to be disposable and insulated. Price-wise, while the coffee beans may be relatively inexpensive on a per-serving basis, the cost of sourcing, processing, and packaging coffee also adds up. However, when comparing the total cost per serving, the cup typically represents a larger expense than the coffee itself. This ratio can vary based on factors such as coffee sourcing and cup design, but in general, the cup tends to be more costly.",
